member.remarks:
 The game loop events are called as follows:

 if ( game is loaded from file ) {
		Run deserializers (constructors of deserialized classes are NOT called)
		Instantiate non-saved dependencies (via their constructors)
		Run methods marked with [InitAfterLoad]
		NewGameInitialized() // for new classes that were added after load
 } else {
		Instantiate all registered dependencies  (via their constructors)
		NewGameCreated()
		while( any( INeedsSimUpdatesForInit.NeedsMoreSimUpdates ) ) {
			perform sim loop
		}
		NewGameInitialized()
 }

 RendererInitState()

 while ( not terminate game ) {
		if ( simulation update is due ) {
			SyncUpdateStart()
			SyncUpdate()
		}

		InputUpdate()
		InputUpdateEnd()

		RenderUpdate()
 }

 Terminate()

member.summary:
Absolute interpolation parameter that represents time between last two sim updates. Values are from 0 to 1.
Intended usage:

// Interpolation:
float value = MafiMath.Lerp(lastState, currentState, AbsoluteT);

// On update-state:
lastState = currentState;
currentState = newState;

Advantage of this interpolation is that is does not have to store current value, it is directly computed.
However, your implementation have to store previous simulation state, current (latest) simulation state, and
those two can produce interpolated value (that is usually stored, too).

On the other hand  does not require to store previous simulation state.

Relative interpolation parameter that represents amount of change between last state (not simulation state)
and current simulation state. Values are from 0 to 1. Intended usage:

// Interpolation:
float value = MafiMath.Lerp(value, currentState, RelativeT);

// On update-state:
currentState = newState;
// Do not do: 'value = currentState;' before the assignment of the new state value.

A big advantage of this interpolation is that you have to store only the last simulation state. Together with
current value you can compute a new value. Unlike with  you do not have to keep two
states in order to do the interpolation. If the state is large this can create large savings in memory and
CPU.

Please keep in mind that the logic behind this interpolation parameter is smart to automatically adjust the
values to varying lengths of frames and sim updates. Do not set new value on copy-state!

             JSON-based configuration for a mod. Place a config.json file in your mod's root directory
             (alongside manifest.json) to define configurable parameters. The framework loads the file
             automatically, persists values in save files, and provides a settings UI for players.


Supported types: double, int, bool, string. All JSON numbers are treated as double
             by default. Set "is_integer": true to get an int parameter instead.


Example config.json:

             {
                 "maxSpeed": {
                     "default": 100,
                     "is_integer": true,
                     "description": "Maximum vehicle speed",
                     "min": 0,
                     "max": 500
                 },
                 "speedMultiplier": {
                     "default": 1.5,
                     "description": "Global speed multiplier",
                     "min": 0.1,
                     "max": 10.0
                 },
                 "enableDebug": {
                     "default": false,
                     "description": "Enable debug logging"
                 },
                 "prefix": {
                     "default": "MyLog",
                     "description": "Log prefix",
                     "max_length": 20,
                     "regex": "^[a-zA-Z0-9]+$"
                 }
             }



Reading values in your mod:

             public override void EarlyInit(DependencyResolver resolver) {
                 int speed = JsonConfig.GetInt("maxSpeed");
                 double mult = JsonConfig.GetDouble("speedMultiplier");
                 bool debug = JsonConfig.GetBool("enableDebug");
                 string pfx = JsonConfig.GetString("prefix");

                 // React to mid-game setting changes:
                 JsonConfig.OnValueChanged += paramName => {
                     if (paramName == "maxSpeed") { /* update logic */ }
                 };
             }



Parameter fields:


default (required) - default value, determines parameter type

description (optional) - shown in settings UI

isInteger (optional, bool) - treat numeric parameter as int instead of double

min, max (optional, numeric) - value range for int/double parameters

maxLength (optional, string) - maximum character count

regex (optional, string) - validation pattern



Save compatibility: Parameters added in newer mod versions get their defaults.
             Parameters removed from config.json are silently dropped from old saves. Numeric type
             changes (int to double or vice versa) are coerced automatically. Incompatible type
             changes (e.g. string to int) fall back to the default value.

